<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>SINGLE REDUCTION CARRIERS: ROCKWELL - REASSEMBLE - ADJUST THICKNESS OF SHIM PACK FOR THE PINION CAGE (DEPTH
        OF PINION)
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc id="hl1400613" svcproctype="assemble" graphiccount="3">
        <title>ADJUST THICKNESS OF SHIM PACK FOR THE PINION CAGE (DEPTH OF PINION)</title>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Use this procedure if a new drive pinion and ring gear set is installed, or if the depth of the
                    drive pinion has to be adjusted (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400678">Figure 78</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <figure id="f1400678" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1400678" filename="../figg14/g1400678.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Figure 78. Adjust Thickness of Shim Pack For Pinion Cage</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Measure the thickness of the old shim pack that was removed from under the pinion cage with
                a micrometer. Record the measurement for later use (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400679">Figure 79</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400679" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400679" filename="../figg14/g1400679.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 79. Measure Thickness of Old Shim Pack</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Look at the pinion cone ("PC") variation number on the old drive pinion that is being
                replaced. Record the number for later use. If ("PC") variation number cannot be located, assemble gear
                set with shim pack thickness found in Step 1 (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400680">Figure 80</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400680" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400680" filename="../figg14/g1400680.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 80. Pinion Cone Variation Number Location</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The pinion cone number can be either 1,000th of an inch or 100ths of a millimeter. See the
                        following examples.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <para>PC+3, PC-3, +3 or -3 equal .003 inch.</para>
            <para>PC+ .03, PC-.03 mm, + .03 mm or -.03 equal .03 mm</para>
            <para>To change inches to millimeters, multiply inches by 25.40</para>
            <para>To change millimeters to inches, multiply millimeters by 0.039</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If the old pinion cone number is a plus (+), subtract the number from the old shim pack
                thickness that was measured in Step 1.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If the old pinion cone number is a minus (-), add the number to the old shim pack thickness
                that was measured in Step 1.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The value calculated in Step 3 or 4 is the thickness of the standard shim pack, without a
                        variation.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Look at the pinion cone ("PC") variation number on the new drive pinion that will be
                installed. Record the number for later use.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If the new pinion cone number is a plus (+), add the number to the standard shim pack
                thickness that was calculated in Step 3 or 4.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If the new pinion cone number is a minus (-), subtract the number from the standard shim
                pack thickness that was calculated in Step 3 or 4.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The value calculated in Step 3 or 4 is the thickness of the new shim pack that will be
